# Achilles Recovery Clinical Positions - Single Source of Truth

These are the final, agreed-upon positions for all contentious aspects of Achilles rupture recovery. Use these consistently across ALL content.

## Treatment

1. **Surgery vs Non-Surgical**: Non-surgical is first-line; surgery only for specific indications (large gap, elite athletes, etc.)
2. **VACOped vs Aircast Boot**: Both produce excellent outcomes; compliance matters more than brand
3. **Early Weight-Bearing**: Immediate weight-bearing as tolerated from day 1
4. **Night Splint Timing**: From boot fitting (non-op), or 2 weeks post-surgery (wound healing)
5. **Boot Removal**: Week 10-12, criteria-based within that window
6. **Tendon Gap Size**: One factor among many (activity level, age, etc.)
7. **Blood Thinners**: 4-6 weeks duration (through full equinus phase), oral tablets preferred for compliance
8. **PRP Therapy**: Insufficient evidence, not recommended (Path 2 Trial)
9. **Shock Wave Therapy**: Limited evidence, not recommended
10. **Imaging**: Usually helpful but not always necessary

## Rehabilitation

11. **Physiotherapy Start**: Week 3-6 (early physio)
12. **Aggressive Stretching**: AVOID until tendon fully healed (12-18 months). Tightness resolves naturally.
13. **Wedge Removal**: Follow schedule exactly, never accelerate
14. **Boot Weaning**: Gradual over 1-2 weeks (few hours/day increasing)
15. **Heel Lifts During Transition**: Always use initially (0.5-1cm)
16. **Eccentric vs Concentric**: To be determined (position #22 unresolved)
17. **Orthotics**: Short-term only, wean off after transition

## Milestones & Return

18. **Single-Leg Heel Raises**: 25+ reps (gold standard), ideally >90% symmetry with other side
19. **Return to Running**: Criteria-based only (25+ heel raises etc.), timing secondary
20. **Return to Sport**: 9 months typical, but criteria-based not time-based. 85% symmetry for sport clearance.
21. **Re-Rupture Rate**: 3-5% (low but not negligible)

## Long-Term Expectations

22. **Calf Asymmetry**: Some permanent difference is normal. Functional strength matters more than size.
23. **Tendon Thickening**: Normal, permanent, doesn't affect function
24. **Age / Activity Level**: Factors among many, neither is determinative alone

## Supportive Care

25. **Nutrition**: Helpful but not essential; balanced diet sufficient
26. **Smoking/Lifestyle**: Important; lifestyle factors affect recovery
27. **Elevation**: Only important post-surgery (2 weeks, 12 hrs/day)
28. **Ice vs Heat**: Ice for swelling, heat for stiffness
29. **Compression**: 2 weeks on opposite leg after surgery, otherwise not important
30. **Psychological Support**: Important; address if present (kinesiophobia, anxiety, depression)

## Usage Rules

- **Consistency is critical** across all articles, lessons, and content
- If a position conflicts with a clinician's protocol, note that guidance varies by clinician/country and patients should follow their own medical team
- When evidence is unclear, use these positions as the standard
- Position #16 (eccentric vs concentric) needs finalising before use in content
